proof.p:
Let x \in A\cap (B \cup C):
\begin{split} x \in A \cap (B \cup C) & \Rightarrow x\in A \textrm{ and } (x\in B\textrm{ or } x\in C)\\ & \quad \textrm{def. of union and intersection}\\ & \Rightarrow (x \in A\textrm{ and }x\in B)\textrm{ or } (x\in A\textrm{ and }x\in C)\\ &\quad \textrm{distributive law of logic}\\ & \Rightarrow (x \in A \cap B) \textrm{ or } (x \in A \cap C)\\ &\quad \textrm{def. of intersection}\\ & \Rightarrow x \in (A \cap B) \cup (A \cap C)\\ &\quad \textrm{def. of union} \end{split}
We must also prove (b) (A\cap B) \cup (A\cap C)\subseteq A \cap (B \cup C).

li.p:
(\supseteq)This half of the proof is bit tricky.  Let  n \in 2\mathbb{Z} \cap 3\mathbb{Z}.  Since  n \in 2\mathbb{Z}, n=2m for some integer m; and since n \in 3\mathbb{Z}, n=2j for some integer j
		\begin{split}
			1 = 3\cdot 1 -2 \cdot 1 &\Rightarrow m = 3m - 2m\\
						& \Rightarrow m= 3m - 3j\\
						& \Rightarrow m = 3(m-j)\\
						& \Rightarrow n = 6(m-j) \in 6\mathbb{Z}
		\end{split}
